ith authorization2star  aAs more and more corporations operate around the globe, the development of an international perspective on industrial relations becomes increasingly urgent. Toward that end, the contributors to Workplace Industrial Relations and the Global Challenge examine the workplace itself. On the basis of ethnographic case studies and comparative data, they conclude that global economic forces and transnational corporations are, indeed, driving industrial relations initiatives. However, national and workplace cultures, as well as state policies, still strongly affect the ways in which cooperation and conflict are negotiated on the shop floor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aComparative industrial relations. 0aComparative management. 0aIndustrial managementvCase studies. 0aIndustrial sociologyvCase studies. 0aWork environmentvCase studies. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aInternational Studies. 4aLabor History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aBelanger, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBélanger, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBélanger, Jacques, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEdwards, P. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, P. K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrenkel, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaiven, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaiven, Larry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerzenberg, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKay, Chung Yuen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 